    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{10m+7}{m}}}{{\frac{m+4}{m}}}}</m> = <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{10m+7}{m+4}, m\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{10m+7}{m}}}{{\frac{m+4}{m}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{10m+7}{m}}</m> and <m>{\frac{m+4}{m}}</m>, which is <m>{m}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{10m+7}{m}}}{{\frac{m+4}{m}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{10m+7}{m}}\cdot{m}}{{\frac{m+4}{m}}\cdot{m}} \\
    \amp = {\frac{10m+7}{m+4}, m\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since <m>{m}</m> was canceled, <m>m \ne 0</m> is in a lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
